<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF76FB93FDA4FBCE" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" box="[151,580,1045,1072]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Size. Attains about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F73FFE4FE90FB93FE56FBD1" box="[369,438,1045,1072]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="cm" value="17.0">17 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F73FFE4FF26FBBFFE8CF8C5" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF26FBBFFC60FACA" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Morphology. D VI + I,12–13; A I,12–13; P 22–23. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FCE9FBBFFC52FBB2" bold="true" box="[776,946,1081,1107]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Body elongate</emphasis>
, the depth 
<quantity id="2E379B383F73FFE4FBD1FBBFFB41FBB2" box="[1072,1185,1081,1108]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5367" metricValueMax="1.651" metricValueMin="1.4223999999999999" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="in" value="6.05" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.6">5.6–6.5 in</quantity>
standard length. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FA85FBBFFC67FB96" bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Eyes protruding, their upper part well above dorsal profile of head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F73FFE4FC79FBDBFC0DFB99" box="[920,1005,1117,1144]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601711" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601711/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
), each topped by a short fleshy knob. A narrow dermal crest present on nape. Caudal peduncle deep, almost as deep as body. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FB9BFB07FD6DFB5E" bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Spines of first dorsal fin elongate, each ending in a short filament</emphasis>
. Dorsal and anal fins long-based. Pelvic fins united to form a disc. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FF76FB4FFE73FB02" bold="true" box="[151,403,1225,1251]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Caudal fin lanceolate</emphasis>
, nearly twice as long as head (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F73FFE4FD04FB4FFCD8FB05" box="[741,824,1225,1252]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601711" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601711/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Scales on body ctenoid posteriorly, becoming cycloid anteriorly below middle of first dorsal fin, no scales on cheek, opercle, and prepectoral area (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F73FFE4FB37FB6BFF34FACD" author="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K." pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref62939" refString="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K. (2015) A revision of the fish genus Oxyurichthys (Gobioidei: Gobiidae) with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 3988 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3988.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Pezold &amp; Larson 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Scales small, at best visible on body as pattern of pale dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF26FAB3FC6BF9E2" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Live coloration. Yellowish to greenish gray dorsally, abdomen whitish, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FBF1FAB3FE3BFA92" bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">with a midlateral row 6 slightly elongate, blackish blotches,</emphasis>
the first blotch on pectoral-fin base, the last on mid caudal peduncle at caudal-fin base (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F73FFE4FF41FAFBFF15FA79" box="[160,245,1405,1432]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601711" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601711/files/figure.png" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
), sometimes alternating with 5 smaller dark spots. Head with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FC5CFAFBFAEEFA76" bold="true" box="[957,1294,1405,1431]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">a broad dark bar below eye</emphasis>
, indistinctly edged with a pale blue line, followed by a row of dark blotches across operculum. Males with a series of oblique iridescent blue streaks on body, the first below origin of first dorsal fin; membranes of both dorsal fins with yellowish marks, forming longitudinal stripes, separated by short blue stripes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF26F98BFD46F9C9" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" box="[199,678,1549,1576]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F73FFE4FE9EF988FD7FF9C6" authorityName="Goren &amp; Stern" authorityYear="2021" box="[383,671,1549,1576]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Cryptocentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="steinhardti">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F73FFE4FE9EF988FD7FF9C6" box="[383,671,1549,1576]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Cryptocentrus steinhardti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF26F9B7FB10F98E" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Habitat. Inhabits silty sand or mud substrata of sheltered bays or estuaries, from the shallows to depths of 
<quantity id="2E379B383F73FFE4FABDF9B7FA78F9AD" box="[1372,1432,1585,1612]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
; takes refuge in a burrow, but is able to dive quickly into mud if threatened when away from shelter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F73FFE4FF26F9FFFE8CF8C5" blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Geographic distribution. In the native area restricted to the Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F73FFE4FC5DF9FFFB5CF975" author="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K." box="[956,1212,1657,1684]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref62939" refString="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K. (2015) A revision of the fish genus Oxyurichthys (Gobioidei: Gobiidae) with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 3988 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3988.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Pezold &amp; Larson 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The most common Lessepsian goby migrant in the Mediterranean, where reported from 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F73FFE4FC77F91BFC05F956" box="[918,997,1693,1719]" name="Greece" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Greece</collectingCountry>
at Kastellorizo Island (
